
Operators

Operators are the building blocks of logic and computation in any language. 
They perform operations on variables and values.

We'll go through every type â€” arithmetic, relational, logical, bitwise, assignment, conditional, 
and special operators.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. Categories of Operators

| Category              | Description                               | Example                            |                         |        |
| --------------------- | ----------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------- | ----------------------- | ------ |
| Arithmetic            | Performs mathematical operations          | `+`, `-`, `*`, `/`, `%`            |                         |        |
| Relational            | Compares two values                       | `==`, `!=`, `>`, `<`, `>=`, `<=`   |                         |        |
| Logical               | Combines boolean expressions              | `&&`, `||`, `!`                            |                         | `, `!` |
| Bitwise               | Works on bits                             | `&`, `                             | `, `^`, `~`, `<<`, `>>` |        |
| Assignment            | Assigns values                            | `=`, `+=`, `-=`, `*=`, `/=`, `%=`  |                         |        |
| Conditional / Ternary | Short-form if-else                        | `condition ? value1 : value2`      |                         |        |
| Increment / Decrement | Increases or decreases value              | `++`, `--`                         |                         |        |
| Special               | Includes type, membership, identity, etc. | `instanceof` (Java), `is` (Python) |                         |        |
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. Arithmetic Operators
ðŸ§  Note:
Division / in Python 3 always gives a float, while // gives integer division.
In Java and C++, integer division truncates decimals.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3. Relational Operators
| Language | Example                     | Description                                                         |
| -------- | --------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Java     | `a > b`, `a == b`, `a != b` | Compares numbers or objects (use `.equals()` for strings)           |
| C++      | `a > b`, `a == b`           | Works for primitive types; custom objects need operator overloading |
| Python   | `a > b`, `a == b`           | Can chain: `a < b < c`                                              |
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Comparison method: Logical Operator (==)
What it compares: Memory Addresses (References)
Use Case: Use for primitive types (like int, boolean, char) to check if their values 
are identical. Avoid for Objects (like Strings).

Comparison method: .equals() Method
What it compares: Actual Character Content (Value)
Use Case: Use for Objects (like String, Date, List) to check if the data they hold is 
logically equivalent. Always use this for Strings.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4. Logical Operators
| Operator     | Meaning     | Example (Java/C++)  | Example (Python)     |        
| ------------ | ----------- | ------------------- | -------------------- | 
| `&&` / `and` | Logical AND | `(a > 5 && b < 10)` | `(a > 5 and b < 10)` |        
| `||` / `or`  | Logical OR  | `(a > 5 || b < 10)` | `(a > 5 or b < 10)`  |
| `!` / `not`  | Logical NOT | `!(a > 5)`          | `not (a > 5)`        |         
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5. Bitwise Operators

Work on bits, not numerical values directly.
| Operator | Description | Example                      |   
| -------- | ----------- | ---------------------------- | 
| `&`      | Bitwise AND | `5 & 3 â†’ 1`                  |    
| `|`      | Bitwise OR  | `5 | 3 â†’ 7`                  |
| `^`      | XOR         | `5 ^ 3 â†’ 6`                  |  
| `~`      | Bitwise NOT | `~5 â†’ -6` (Twoâ€™s complement) |    
| `<<`     | Left shift  | `5 << 1 â†’ 10`                |    
| `>>`     | Right shift | `5 >> 1 â†’ 2`                 |   

ðŸ§  Language Note:
Java and C++ handle >> as arithmetic shift for signed integers.
Java also has >>> (unsigned right shift). Python lacks >>>.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
6. Assignment Operators
| Example  | Meaning     |
| -------- | ----------- |
| `a += 5` | `a = a + 5` |
| `a -= 5` | `a = a - 5` |
| `a *= 5` | `a = a * 5` |
| `a /= 5` | `a = a / 5` |
| `a %= 5` | `a = a % 5` |
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
7. Increment / Decrement Operators
| Language | Example         | Notes                          |
| -------- | --------------- | ------------------------------ |
| Java     | `a++`, `++a`    | Post & pre increment supported |
| C++      | `a++`, `++a`    | Same as Java                   |
| Python   | âŒ Not available | Use `a += 1` or `a -= 1`       |
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
8. Conditional (Ternary) Operator
| Language | Syntax                                 | Example                         | Output        |
| -------- | -------------------------------------- | ------------------------------- | ------------- |
| Java     | `condition ? true_val : false_val`     | `int result = (a > b) ? a : b;` | Larger number |
| C++      | Same as Java                           | `int max = (a > b) ? a : b;`    | Larger number |
| Python   | `true_val if condition else false_val` | `result = a if a > b else b`    | Larger number |
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
9. Special Operators
| Language | Operator           | Meaning                       |
| -------- | ------------------ | ----------------------------- |
| Java     | `instanceof`       | Checks object type            |
| C++      | `sizeof`, `typeid` | Memory size and type info     |
| Python   | `is`, `in`         | Identity and membership tests |

// Java
Object obj = "Hello!";
if (obj instanceof String) System.out.println("It's a string!");

// C++
cout << sizeof(int) << endl; // 4 bytes

# Python
if "a" in "apple":
    print("Found!")
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
10. Operator Precedence & Associativity

| Precedence Level | Operators            | Associativity | 
| ---------------- | -------------------- | ------------- | 
| Highest          | `()`, `[]`, `.`      | Left to Right | 
| Unary            | `++`, `--`, `!`, `~` | Right to Left | 
| Multiplicative   | `*`, `/`, `%`        | Left to Right | 
| Additive         | `+`, `-`             | Left to Right | 
| Relational       | `<`, `>`, `<=`, `>=` | Left to Right |
| Equality         | `==`, `!=`           | Left to Right |
| Logical          | `&&`, `||`, `!`      | Left to Right |
| Assignment       | `=`, `+=`, `-=`      | Right to Left |

BODMAS and PEMDAS are acronyms for the order of operations in mathematics, used to ensure consistent evaluation of expressions.

BODMAS (used in the UK, India, and Commonwealth countries):
Brackets, Orders (exponents, roots), Division, Multiplication, Addition, Subtraction

PEMDAS (used in the US):
Parentheses, Exponents, Multiplication, Division, Addition, Subtraction 
Despite the different names, they represent the same rule:

Multiplication and division have equal precedence and are performed left to right.
Addition and subtraction have equal precedence and are also performed left to right.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
11. Common Mistakes & Notes

| Mistake                              | Explanation                                       |                       
| ------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------------------- |
| `a = b == c` confusion               | `==` evaluated first; use parentheses for clarity |                       
| Mixing bitwise and logical           | `&` and `|`are bitwise;`&&`and `||` are logical   |
| Integer division in Python           | Use `//` for integer division                     |                       
| Using `is` instead of `==` in Python | `is` checks identity, not equality                |                       
